<p>Please excuse the code mess. We are learning!</p>
<p>We have several problems all around the WPI MecanumDrive class. We are defining the object. Calling the constructor with the 4 motors in teleop init. Then calling the .driveCartesian() with joystick inputs in the teleop peroidic.</p>
<p>Problem 1: As it is right now we are getting the following error repeating. “Error at edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.MotorSafety.check(MotorSafety.java:140)MecanumDrive…” basically the mecanumDrive (actually driveCartesian()) is not being called often enough. There shouldn’t be anything that would hang Teleop periodic. I have tried removing writes to network tables and anything that might slow down the code but nothing seems to be removing the error.</p>
<p>Problem 2: Initially we constructed the mecanumDrive in robot init instead of teleop init. We moved it because our Auto wasn’t working at all. We were directing the drive motors to positions with <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> but the motors were jerking on and off rapidly. Basically the motors were getting told to go to position in the auto periodic but the mecanumDrive was causing the motors to get a percentOutput = 0 command and it was rapidly switching between the two. Moving the mecanumDrive to teleop Init fixed the issue, however if we run teleop and then run auto the same thing will happen since the mecanumDrive object has been created. Only solution is to restart robot. This work around is ok, however, we want to switch to a velocity pid on our drive but want to switch back to our normal mecanumDrive. I need a way to disable mecanumDrive. I would think that not calling driveCartisian() would stop it, however that does not appear to be the case. Doing some more research tonight I might try mecanumDrive.close() to see what that does tomorrow but any info on how to command mecanumDrive to relinquish control of the motors would be great.</p>
<p>Thank you in advance for your help!</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-03-06T04:21:52.453Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":11,"reads":54,"readers_count":53,"score":65.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":457505,"topic_slug":"help-with-basic-mechanum-drive-using-wpilib","display_username":"bharrison6","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/FRC-Team-3843/FRC-2024/blob/main/2024Robot/src/main/java/frc/robot/Robot.java","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"FRC-2024/2024Robot/src/main/java/frc/robot/Robot.java at main · FRC-Team-3843/FRC-2024 · GitHub","clicks":14}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":22201,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/help-with-basic-mechanum-drive-using-wpilib/457505/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3325384,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2024-03-06T04:42:30.302Z","cooked":"<p>Looking through your code, my first thought is “<em>PLEASE</em> look into the command-based pattern…”.<br>
It’s likely a bit late to start from scratch this year, but learning that would be a great off-season project!</p>
<p>As for your issues…</p>
<p>Problem 1: When does this error appear? Repeatedly/all the time? Just during auto? Only once or twice when the code starts?  MotorSafety is a safety feature you generally don’t want to disable.  If it appears a couple times during boot up, it can safely be ignored, but happening repeatedly would generally be indicative of you doing something wrong.  It should go away if you’re calling one of the drive methods on the MecanumDrive object every periodic iteration (even if the value you’re giving it is 0).</p>
<p>Problem 2: You definitely want this object constructed in the constructor or robotinit method.  Is there a reason you’re directly commanding the motors instead of using the MecanumDrive object in your autonomous modes?  This would seem to be the source of your problem when instantiating that object in robotInit()</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-03-06T04:42:30.302Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":31,"readers_count":30,"score":11.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":457505,"topic_slug":"help-with-basic-mechanum-drive-using-wpilib","display_username":"Fletch","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":9105,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades"},"post_url":"/t/help-with-basic-mechanum-drive-using-wpilib/457505/2","custom_user_title":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3325397,"name":"bharrison6","username":"bharrison6","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/b/ecae2f/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-06T04:53:56.135Z","cooked":"<p>Agree on command-based pattern, but your right it’s a bit late to do a rewrite.</p>
<p>Problem 1: The error occurs constantly during teleop. You are correct, this is indicative that something is wrong, I am just not sure what is wrong. As called in the API I am calling the mecaniumDrive.driveCartesian(yaxis, xaxis, zaxis) periodically during teleop periodic.</p>
<p>Problem 2: As mentioned we are using the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> position control on the motors to move to position during Auto. This is far more repeatable than using mecaniumDrive with joystick inputs with some type of time variable. We moved the constructor of mecaniumDrive to teleop init because it is interfering with the position control. Essentially mecaniumDrive was directing the motors to stop (percentOutput = 0) during each loop and at the same time we were telling the motor to move using position control to a certain position each loop.  As I had mentioned as soon as you construct mecaniumDrive you loose any ability to manually control the motors. There should be a way to stop mecaniumDrive from controlling those resources. That is what I am looking for.</p>
<p>Thanks for looking at it!</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-03-06T04:53:56.135Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":30,"readers_count":29,"score":11.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":457505,"topic_slug":"help-with-basic-mechanum-drive-using-wpilib","display_username":"bharrison6","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":9105,"username":"Fletch1373","name":"Fletch","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":22201,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/help-with-basic-mechanum-drive-using-wpilib/457505/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3325413,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2024-03-06T05:31:15.857Z","cooked":"<p>Definitely odd…</p>
<p>The MecanumDrive constructor generally accepts motorcontroller objects.  I see a version that accepts consumers, which I presume is what you’re using (whether intentional or not, I’m not sure).  I’ve never done it that way, so maybe there’s something odd about it?  I don’t see anything weird in the <a href="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/drive/MecanumDrive.java" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">source for that class though</a>.  Feel free to take a look through.  In fact, I see it <a href="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/drive/MecanumDrive.java#L222" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">explicitly calling feed()</a>.</p>
<details>
<summary>
Just a mild critique if you're open to it</summary>
<p>You can use <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/MathUtil.html#applyDeadband(double,double)" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">MathUtil.applyDeadband(…)</a> to simplify <a href="https://github.com/FRC-Team-3843/FRC-2024/blob/main/2024Robot/src/main/java/frc/robot/Robot.java#L270-L282" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">these lines</a> down to:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">robotDrive.driveCartesian(
    MathUtil.applyDeadband(controller1.getLeftY(), deadband),
    -MathUtil.applyDeadband(controller1.getRightX(), deadband),
    -MathUtil.applyDeadband(controller1.getLeftX(), deadband)
);
</code></pre>
